{{refimprove|date=September 2014}} {{Wiktionary}} In [[grammar]], '''denominal verbs''' are [[verb]]s derived from [[noun]]s. Many languages have regular [[Morphological derivation|morphological indicators]] to create denominal verbs.
==English== [[English language|English]] examples are ''to school'', from ''school'', meaning to instruct; ''to shelve'', from ''shelf'', meaning to put on shelves; and ''to symbolize'', from ''symbol'', meaning to be a symbol for.
Some common denominalizing affixes in English are ''-ize/-ise'' (e.g., ''summarize''), ''-ify'' (e.g., ''classify''), ''-ate'' (e.g., ''granulate''), ''en-'' (e.g., ''enslave''), ''be-'' (e.g., ''behead''), and [[Conversion (word formation)|zero]] or ''-∅'' (e.g.,, ''school'').<ref name="gottfurcht"/>
A variety of semantic relations are expressed between the base noun X and the derived verb; there is no simple relationship between the affix and the semantic relation:<ref name="gottfurcht">Carolyn A. Gottfurcht, ''Denominal Verb Formation in English'', Ph.D. dissertation, Northwestern University, 2008 [https://www.linguistics.northwestern.edu/documents/dissertations/linguistics-research-graduate-dissertations-gottfurchtdissertation2007.pdf full text]</ref> * [[resultative]]: to make something into an X, e.g., ''victimize'', ''cash'' * [[locative case|locative]]: to put something in X, e.g., ''box'', ''hospitalize'' * [[instrumental case|instrumental]]: to use X, e.g., ''sponge'', ''hammer'' * [[ablative case|ablative]], [[privative]]: to remove X from something, e.g., ''shell (peas)'', ''behead'', ''bone'' * [[ornative case|ornative]]: to add X to something or to cover something with X, e.g., ''rubberize'', ''salt'' * [[similative]]: to act like or resemble X, e.g., ''tyrannize'', ''guard'' * performative: to do or perform X, e.g., ''botanize'', ''tango''
==Rgyalrong== In [[Rgyalrong languages]], denominal derivation are extremely developed and have given rise to [[incorporation (linguistics)|incorporating]] and [[antipassive]] constructions (Jacques 2012, 2014).
==Latin== Many Latin verbs are denominal.<ref name=moreland_fleischer>{{cite book |last1=Moreland |first1=Floyd L. |last2=Fleischer |first2=Rita M. |date=1990 |title=Latin: An Intensive Course |location=London, England |publisher=University of California Press |page=29 |isbn= 0520031830}}</ref> For example, the first [[Latin declension|declension]] verb ''[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/corono#Latin coronare]'' (to crown) is derived from ''corona'' (a crown),<ref name=moreland_fleischer /> and the fourth declension verbs ''mollire'' (to soften) and ''servire'' (to serve) are derived from ''mollis'' (soft) and ''servus'' (a slave) respectively.<ref>{{cite book |last=Fortson |first=Benjamin W. IV |date=2004 |title=Indo-European Languages and Culture |publisher=Blackwell |isbn=978-1-4051-0315-2 |section=13.13}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Deverbal noun]], where the noun is formed from the verb
