[[File:Roman Empire - Africa Proconsularis (125 AD).svg|thumb|right|[[Africa Proconsularis]] (125 AD)]]
'''Henchir-Aïn-Dourat''', also known as ''Ad-Duwayrat'' or ''Henchir Durat'', is a former [[Roman Empire|Roman]]&ndash;[[Berbers|Berber]] [[civitas]] and [[archaeology|archaeological site]] in [[Tunisia]]. It is located at 36.767496[[north|n]], 9.524142[[east|e]], in the hills just north of [[Toukabeur]] and 15.3&nbsp;km from [[Majaz al Bab|Majāz al Bāb]]. It was an ancient [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[diocese]].

==History==
The ruins have been identified as the remains of Uccula a [[municipium]] of the [[Roman province|province]] of [[Africa Proconsularis]] during the [[Roman Empire]],<ref>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/former/t1899.htm Titular Episcopal See of  Uccula ].</ref><ref>Barrington Atlas, 2000, pl. 32 E3</ref> and which was active from 330 BC – AD 640.  The ruins at Henchir-Aïn-Dourat have been surveyed,<ref>René Cagnat & Salomon Reinach, Découvertes de villes nouvelles en Tunisie ''Comptes rendus des séances de l'Académie des Inscriptions et Belles-Lettres'' (1885) Vol.29, Num,3  pp. 252-260.</ref> and include a statue of mars.<ref>Abdellatif Mrabet, ''In Africa and in Hispania'' (Edicions Universitat Barcelona, 2007 ) p176.</ref> An inscription in the ruins honors [[Constantine the Great|Constantine]] as "beyond the other emperors" and "unconquered".<ref>Raymond Van Dam, ''Remembering Constantine at the Milvian Bridge'' (Cambridge University Press, 29 April 2011) p171.</ref> and another earlier in its history  honours Divus Titus.<ref>Duncan Fishwick, ''The Imperial Cult in the Latin West'' (BRILL, 2002) p199.</ref>

Before the [[Roman Empire|Roman]]s the town <ref>Mark Vessey, ''A Companion to Augustine'' (John Wiley & Sons, 21 May 2012 ) p24.</ref> was in the tribal area of the ''[[Afri]]'', a [[Berbers|Berber]] confederation.

The civitas was also the [[cathedra|seat]] of an ancient Christian [[bishopric]], which survives today as a [[titular see]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]].<ref>[http://www.apostolische-nachfolge.de/titulare_u.htm Apostolische Nachfolge – Titularsitze]</ref><ref>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/former/t1899.htm Uccula] at 'gcatholic.org</ref>

